input: Campese berates whingeing England  Former Australian wing David Campese has told England to stop whingeing in the wake of their defeat to Ireland.
England coach Andy Robinson lambasted referee Jonathan Kaplan for costing them the game after disallowing tries from Mark Cueto and Josh Lewsey.
But Campese told BBC Sport: "Robinson is living up to England reputation as whingeing Poms.
"Stop going on about it as who really cares?
They are acting like they are the first team to be cheated of a win."
England are contemplating a complaint to the International Rugby Board after potential "tries" by Cueto in the first half and Lewsey late on were ruled out without recourse to the video referee.
But Campese added: "Scotland could have beaten France in the same way, but do you see them whingeing?
"Basically, things did not go England way and, in typical fashion, they make more of it when they believe they have lost unfairly."
England are second bottom in the Six Nations table following defeats by Wales, France and Ireland.
But although Campese admitted he was surprised about their current predicament, he insisted England were "no longer world class".
"England are beginning to realise that being world champions does not mean you deserve to win every game," he said.
"They lost a few key players and suddenly everyone is realised the ones on the fringes were not all that good in the first place.
"Added to that, the senior players are not standing up and they can not do anything when the pressure mounts."
Campese, a veteran of 101 international caps, said full-back Jason Robinson would now be the sole Englishman in his World XV.
Robinson has been blamed for poor leadership in the tournament, while his coach has been castigated for appointing a full-back captain.
"I agree that you can not captain from full-back," said Campese.
"You need someone in the thick of the action, and it is very hard to give orders from all the way back there.
"Some people are leaders and some are not.
He is not but there is no one who stands out in England pack - no clear-cut leaders."
Campese, though, defended coach Andy Robinson, who he believes was the "only choice" after Sir Clive Woodward resignation.
But he blamed "a lack of talent in the England camp" for making the current coach look poor.
England face a potential wooden spoon match against Italy on 12 March.
And the ex-Wallaby added: "If England lost that, they would be in bloody turmoil.
That said, I do not think they will."
Campese has tipped Wales to win both the Six Nations and Grand Slam come the end of the tournament.
"It is been a surprising tournament," he said, "and maybe Ireland have a little bit more talent overall.
"But playing at home is a major boost.
And the possible Grand Slam decider at the Millennium Stadium will be just too much for the Irish."
